In our technique of ASO with UVP closure of VSD, the right ventricle can decompress in the immediate postoperative period into the left ventricle whenever the pulmonary artery pressure is raised. This may produce instances of systemic desaturation, but we have found this to be well tolerated without hemodynamic compromise. Follow-up transthoracic echocardiograms have shown a reduction in the estimated pulmonary artery pressures. This would be associated with reversal of the flow across an open fenestration, but since the valved patch VSD closure allows unidirectional flow only, it closes itself off, preventing any left-to-right shunt. Hence, the burden of an additional procedure can be avoided. Therefore, we believe that our technique is advantageous, compared with that proposed by Lei et al. Our experience with this technique in a limited number of patients has provided good results over a mean follow-up period of 10 ± 7.6 months. This cohort needs to be followed up further to ascertain the long-term benefits of this procedure. There may be a role for drugs like bosentan or sildenafil in further reducing the pulmonary pressures and pulmonary vascular resistance;
13
 however, we do not have any specific protocol at this time for using these drugs perioperatively or postoperatively; sildenafil was used postoperatively in some of these patients and is being continued. However, the optimal duration of therapy is uncertain. Later with more experience and follow-up, we may be able to answer this question. Another reason these patients are not treated preoperatively with pulmonary vasodilators is that these patients often come from a rural background and have already come to us late. So the bias is to operate on them earlier and administer dilators postoperatively rather than starting them well before the surgery.
